{{Unreferenced|date=April 2009}}
'''Dual Scan''', also known as dual-scan supertwist nematic or '''DSTN''', is an [[LCD]] technology in which a screen is divided into two sections which are simultaneously refreshed giving faster refresh rate than traditional [[passive matrix]] screens. It is an improved form of [[Super-twisted nematic display|supertwist nematic]] display that offers low power consumption but inferior sharpness and brightness compared to [[TFT LCD|TFT screens]]. For several years (late '90s to early 2000s), TFT screens were only found in high-end [[laptop]]s due to them being more expensive and lower-end laptops offering DSTN screens only. This was at a time when the screen was often the most expensive component of laptops. The price difference between a laptop with DSTN and one with TFT could easily be $400 or more. However, TFT gradually became cheaper and has essentially captured the entire market.

DSTN display quality is poor compared to TFT, with visible noise, smearing, much lower contrast and slow response. Such screens are unsuitable for viewing movies.

