{{Infobox medical intervention | name = Nasal expiratory positive airway pressure | image = | caption = | alt = | pronounce = | synonyms = | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | ICD9unlinked = | MeshID = | LOINC = | other_codes = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicine = }}
'''Nasal expiratory positive airway pressure''' ('''Nasal EPAP''') is a treatment for [[obstructive sleep apnea]] (OSA) and snoring.<ref name=Wu2015rev>{{cite journal|last1=Wu|first1=H|last2=Yuan|first2=X|last3=Zhan|first3=X|last4=Li|first4=L|last5=Wei|first5=Y|title=A review of EPAP nasal device therapy for obstructive sleep apnea syndrome.|journal=Sleep & breathing = Schlaf & Atmung|date=September 2015|volume=19|issue=3|pages=769–74|pmid=25245174|doi=10.1007/s11325-014-1057-y}}</ref><ref name=Riaz2015rev>{{cite journal|last1=Riaz|first1=M et al. |title=Nasal Expiratory Positive Airway Pressure Devices (Provent) for OSA: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis.|journal=Sleep disorders|date=2015|volume=2015|pages=734798|pmid=26798519|pmc=4699057|doi=10.1155/2015/734798}}</ref>
Contemporary EPAP devices have two small valves that allow air to be drawn in through each nostril, but not exhaled; the valves are held in place by adhesive tabs on the outside of the nose.<ref name=Wu2015rev/> The mechanism by which EPAP may work is not clear; it may be that the resistance to nasal exhalation leads to [[Hypercapnia|a buildup in CO<sub>2</sub>]] which in turn increases [[Control of ventilation#Control of ventilatory pattern|respiratory drive]], or that resistance to exhalation generates pressure that forces the upper airway to open wider.<ref name=Wu2015rev/>
In OSA it appears to be effective to reduce but not eliminate apnea for people with mild to moderate OSA ([[Apnea–hypopnea index]] < 30) and for people who cannot tolerate [[Continuous positive airway pressure|CPAP]], but within those groups it is not clear why some respond and others do not, and the evidence consists of small clinical trials with follow-up no longer than one year.<ref name=Wu2015rev/><ref name=Riaz2015rev/> As of 2015 there was evidence from one small trial that it may be useful in children with OSA.<ref name=Wu2015rev/> It has shown evidence of reducing snoring as well.<ref name=Wu2015rev/><ref name=Riaz2015rev/>
EPAP is unlikely to be effective in people with significant nasal obstruction.<ref name=Wu2015rev/> Side effects that emerged during clinical trials included difficulty breathing, difficulty falling or staying asleep, dry mouth, nasal congestion, headache, difficulty putting on or removing the device, and anxiety.<ref name=Wu2015rev/>
Ventus Medical received FDA [[510K]] clearance for marketing the Provent EPAP device for OSA in 2009.<ref>FDA [http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfpmn/pmn.cfm?id=K090398 ProVent 510K table]</ref><ref>FDA [http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf9/K090398.pdf Provent 510(k) Summary] April 3, 2009</ref> Ventus received 510K clearance for an EPAP device to treat snoring in June 2012.<ref>FDA [http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cdrh/cfdocs/cfpmn/pmn.cfm?id=K120665 InVent 510K table]</ref><ref>FDA [http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf12/K120665.pdf InVent 510(k) Summary] June 12, 2012</ref> Ventus was acquired by Theravent Inc. in 2013.<ref>Staff, Sleep Review. April 19, 2013 [http://www.sleepreviewmag.com/2013/04/ventus-medical-closes-its-doors/ Ventus Medical Closing Its Doors]</ref><ref>Bloomberg [https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=28217159 Ventus profile] Page accessed August 15, 2016</ref>
