{{Underlinked|date=September 2016}}

'''Twine''' is a stand-alone device that uses sensors to detect parts of its environment and that connects to a wifi network to communicate. Rules loaded into the Twine can test for sensor conditions and, based on logic, send messages through email or SMS, make an HTTP request, or light a LED.<ref>{{cite web|title=‘Twine’ seeks to tie up the smart environment|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-11/30/twine-rubber-block|publisher=Wired|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> It can act as a [[data logger]].

The device was created by Supermechanical in the USA from funding raised on [[Kickstarter]]. Their original goal was for $35,000 yet they raised $556,541 from 3,966 backers on January 3, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kickstarter Page for Twine|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/supermechanical/twine-listen-to-your-world-talk-to-the-internet/|accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> 
The product successfully shipped in November 2012.

